            <h1 style="font-size: 34px; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 12px;">Blood Donation Guide</h1>
            <p style="color: #64748b; font-size: 15px; max-width: 760px;">Everything you need to know before, during and after donating blood, including safe transfusion practices and the official Red Cross PH resources.</p>
        </div>

        <div style="display: grid; gap: 24px;">
            <section style="background: #fff; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0; border-radius: 24px; padding: 28px; box-shadow: 0 8px 24px rgba(15, 23, 42, 0.06);">
                <h2 style="font-size: 22px; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 14px;">Before Donating Blood</h2>
                <ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0; color: #475569;">
                    <li style="margin-bottom: 14px;"><strong>Check eligibility:</strong> You should be at least 18 years old, weigh at least 50 kg, be in good health, and meet local donation criteria. Avoid donating if you have recently been ill, had surgery, or are taking medication that may affect donation.</li>
                    <li style="margin-bottom: 14px;"><strong>Eat well:</strong> Have a balanced meal 2–3 hours before donation. Avoid fatty foods just before donating because they can affect testing on your blood sample.</li>
                    <li style="margin-bottom: 14px;"><strong>Hydrate:</strong> Drink plenty of water the day before and the morning of donation. Good hydration helps maintain blood volume and lowers the chance of dizziness.</li>
                    <li style="margin-bottom: 14px;"><strong>Rest well:</strong> Get a full night’s sleep before donation and avoid heavy exercise immediately beforehand.</li>
                    <li style="margin-bottom: 14px;"><strong>Bring ID:</strong> Carry a valid ID and any donor card or medical documentation required by the donation center.</li>
                </ul>
            </section>

            <section style="background: #fff; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0; border-radius: 24px; padding: 28px; box-shadow: 0 8px 24px rgba(15, 23, 42, 0.06);">
                <h2 style="font-size: 22px; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 14px;">During Donation</h2>
                <ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0; color: #475569;">
                    <li style="margin-bottom: 14px;"><strong>Registration and screening:</strong> You will answer health questions and have a short physical check including blood pressure, pulse, temperature and hemoglobin level.</li>
                    <li style="margin-bottom: 14px;"><strong>Comfort and safety:</strong> Sit in a comfortable chair, relax your arm, and let the trained staff place the needle. The procedure typically takes 8–12 minutes for a single donation bag.</li>
                    <li style="margin-bottom: 14px;"><strong>Monitoring:</strong> The team will watch for any discomfort or bruising. Speak up immediately if you feel lightheaded, nauseous, or uncomfortable.</li>
                    <li style="margin-bottom: 14px;"><strong>Standard donation volume:</strong> Most healthy donors give about 450 ml. This volume is replaced by your body over the next few days.</li>
                    <li style="margin-bottom: 14px;"><strong>Safety checks:</strong> Your blood is tested for infections and blood type. Only safe, screened blood is released for transfusion.</li>
                </ul>
            </section>

            <section style="background: #fff; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0; border-radius: 24px; padding: 28px; box-shadow: 0 8px 24px rgba(15, 23, 42, 0.06);">
                <h2 style="font-size: 22px; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 14px;">After Donating Blood</h2>
                <ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0; color: #475569;">
                    <li style="margin-bottom: 14px;"><strong>Rest briefly:</strong> Remain seated for 10–15 minutes after donation, and enjoy the post-donation snack or drink offered by the center.</li>
                    <li style="margin-bottom: 14px;"><strong>Stay hydrated:</strong> Keep drinking water or juice for the remainder of the day. Hydration supports recovery and helps replace the fluid lost during donation.</li>
                    <li style="margin-bottom: 14px;"><strong>Avoid strenuous activity:</strong> Do not do heavy lifting, intense exercise, or strenuous work for the rest of the day. Take it easy and let your body recover.</li>
                    <li style="margin-bottom: 14px;"><strong>Watch for symptoms:</strong> Minor bruising or soreness is normal. If you experience dizziness, prolonged bleeding, swelling, or severe discomfort, contact the donation center or a medical professional.</li>
                    <li style="margin-bottom: 14px;"><strong>Eat iron-rich foods:</strong> Include leafy greens, lean meats, beans, and fortified cereal in your meals to help restore iron levels.</li>
                </ul>
            </section>

            <section style="background: #fff; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0; border-radius: 24px; padding: 28px; box-shadow: 0 8px 24px rgba(15, 23, 42, 0.06);">
                <h2 style="font-size: 22px; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 14px;">Blood Transfusion Facts</h2>
                <ul style="list-style: none; padding: 0; margin: 0; color: #475569;">
                    <li style="margin-bottom: 14px;"><strong>Why transfusions are needed:</strong> Transfusions replace lost blood due to surgery, trauma, chronic illness, anemia, or blood disorders.</li>
                    <li style="margin-bottom: 14px;"><strong>Blood typing:</strong> Matching blood types reduces risk. The main groups are A, B, AB and O, each with Rh-positive or Rh-negative status.</li>
                    <li style="margin-bottom: 14px;"><strong>Compatibility:</strong> O-negative is the universal donor for red cells, while AB-positive is the universal plasma recipient. Always follow health worker guidance.</li>
                    <li style="margin-bottom: 14px;"><strong>Testing and safety:</strong> Donated blood is screened for infections such as HIV, hepatitis, syphilis, and others. Only safe blood is issued for transfusions.</li>
                    <li style="margin-bottom: 14px;"><strong>Potential reactions:</strong> Mild reactions like fever or chills can occur. Serious reactions are rare but should be reported immediately to medical staff.</li>
                    <li style="margin-bottom: 14px;"><strong>Patient care:</strong> Transfusion decisions are based on the patient’s condition and medical history. Health workers monitor the patient before, during, and after transfusion.</li>
                </ul>
            </section>

